Per-instance SSE-subscriber bus event (kfactory.subscribers.changed).

Publishes `kfactory.subscribers.changed` with the absolute per-workspace
subscriber count `{count: N}` on every attach / detach to the
per-instance `/event` SSE endpoint. A WeakMap<Bus.Interface, number>
tracks the live count; each publish carries the post-change total. The
instance bus is workspace-scoped (one per InstanceStore context), so
each publish only reaches plugins running in the same workspace.
Plugins assign their local count from `props.count` to derive a
per-workspace "is anyone watching" signal -- used by the kfactory ntfy
plugin (plugins/ntfy in the kfactory repo) to skip / cancel
notifications when an operator is attached.

Absolute-count semantics rather than `{delta: ±1}`: delta accumulation
can't recover from cold-start asymmetry. A plugin that loads after a
subscriber attached would either miss the first +1 (and notify with an
operator attached) or clamp negative on the first -1 (and stay stuck).
With absolute counts the next publish brings any plugin into sync
regardless of when it loaded.

Why this lives in opencode (and not as a pure plugin trick):
  - There is no plugin-API surface for SSE subscriber state today; the
    HTTP connection lifecycle is invisible to the existing `Plugin.event`
    hook (verified via spec.md decision-log entry on the API audit).
  - The cleanest hook point is the response stream's lifecycle in
    `event.ts` (`Stream.ensuring` for detach, the surrounding generator
    for attach). Adding the publish there is local, ~30 LOC, and uses
    only types already imported in adjacent files.

Stacking: applied AFTER opencode-bearer-and-routing and BEFORE
opencode-kfactory-refresh. The patch touches only event.ts, which
neither neighbour modifies, so the stack is independent in practice.
The flake check `factory-opencode-patch-applies` runs the full
three-patch sequence and fails loudly if any drift is introduced.

